div.div: This project started as a build from Ben Eater's kit. The major components are still the same: Western Design Center 65c02s CPU and 65c22 interface adapter, with 32K static RAM and 32K EEPROM. The use of an Econoreset IC is from suggestions posted to 6502.org; the reset circuit is from the DS1233 datasheet. The use of an 8-bit comparator to reduce the memory reserved for I/O to only 256 bytes is also from 6502.org. However, I'm using two 4-bit comparators instead as they are easier to find. The RS-232 interface on the next page is from the design on steckschwein.de, with minor changes. Inverting the main clock twice to produce a write strobe that runs ahead of PHI2, and then generating a read strobe that trails PHI2, is a trick I remember being used in the 1980s. The diagnostic LED circuitry is my design. Its purpose is to display error codes from a power-on self test (POST) with minimal reliance on the other major components.
